segments.text: College Station, Texas A&M.
Would you introduce yourself please, tell me your full name and maybe a little about your very early career and where you came from and how you got to Texas A&M.
Okay, William Burch Harris.
I was born in Loveland, Colorado.
which is probably, in my opinion, the best place in the world to have been born.
It's right close to the mountains.
And my parents were fairly well aged when I got born, so they sort of let me run my own ship, which was kind of a Belgian outfit.
It gave me a lot of free rein to go fishing when I felt like it and that sort of thing.
It was a good life.
Of course, that was during the Depression when the folks had a farm, which they rented out, which made them, I guess you'd say middle class, but still not much money.
The big thing around Lublin in those days was farming.
Sugar beets?
Are you into sugar beets?
Sugar beets, yeah.
And at that time, they called themselves the cherry capital of the world.
They had many, many cherry orchards.
And during the summer, for example, all those kids and mothers and fathers and other people would be picking cherries.
You could make a lot of money, but in the Depression, a dollar a day wasn't bad.
It's about what I could make.
We had a canning plant there in town, which processed cherries and peas and beans
other things of that nature.
It was the second biggest industry in town, the sugar beet factory being the biggest.
Were you kind of on the edge then of chemical engineering and didn't know it at the time?
Well, not really.
Not too much chemical engineering in Canyon, I guess, for sure.
Well, I'm from Louisiana, and I guess
They really recruited chemical engineers pretty early into the sugar refining process.
That's right.

Most of them had a chemist, they used to call them chemists, but it turns out chem engineers were a little more useful than chemists actually, because the chemistry is pretty well fixed for that business.
Actually, in our town, the best job in town was probably the manager of the sugar plant.
The next best job was being the chemist in the sugar plant.
But anyhow, when I was 16, I, Cornswogged a chance to go to work for the Cooner Empson Company during the summer, which meant I didn't have to pick cherries anymore.
And I got the big sum of 32 cents an hour, which was about double the normal wage, so that was not bad.
No, that's pretty good.
That's K-U-N-E-R. K-U-N-E-R. Yeah.
Did you ever see that?
Oh yeah.
But anyhow, I kind of got in there through the back door.
I met a guy who was a foreman and he kind of liked me I guess.
He had an extra time card he was supposed to be passing out to his old employees and he slipped one to me.
You were hired.
I was hired.
Plant's superintendent came along about a week later and saw me and said, my God, how old are you?
I told him 16, and he looked at me a little bit and finally said, well, bring a letter from your parents saying it's okay.
So I had a job, which was, there weren't too many jobs in those days.
That was a little, I should at least half the town was unemployed, I guess.
A little more than that.
Anyhow, I worked there, finished up high school,
I decided I'd go to, in high school, chemistry was lots of fun.
So, that and the fact that I liked to repair motorcycles and crap like that, the instructor told me I ought to be a team engineer.
It sounded all right to me.
That's all I knew about it.
Went to the University of Colorado.
got out after the usual four years.
Now, at Colorado, was the chemical engineering program in with chemistry?
No, it was a separate department, but I later, after I graduated, found out it was not an accredited college.
So, that got me into a little trouble later on when I wanted to do the registry as a professional engineer, because I hadn't gotten out of an accredited institution.
But anyhow, worked my way through college, didn't have any money.
Actually, the way I did it, I formed a housing co-op, and we rented an old fraternity house that had gone under, hired a housekeeper and cook, and we were in business.
And since I organized it, I got three board meetings for being the dishwasher.
You know, that was a big thing here.
You've probably heard about it, the Kalamata Houses.
Well, it was pretty much in those days.
We had a guy, a prop sponsor, who by today's standards would be a full-fledged communist, that he would offer.
That was the style.
That kind of stuff.
So it worked out real well.
I had that job.
In the summers, of course I went back the next year, when I was seventeen,
and worked at the canning company most of the summer.
When I was 18 I went back and found out that the foreman of the plant was going to quit because he'd gotten a full-time job up in this part working in the diversion of the Big Thompson River.
And about a month before the plant was supposed to start, I went and wondered who the heck my boss was going to be.
So I walked down to the plant, caught the plant manager walking down the sidewalk in front of the building and says, hey, I hear Bert's not coming back.
He says, that's right.
So I said, well, do you have anyone to take his place?
And he looked at me kind of funny and said, well, he'll consider you.
So I kept my mouth shut.
Of course, I had no idea of applying for the job, but about a week later, one of my buddies said,
I went down and asked the same thing.
He wanted to know who his boss was going to be.
The guy said, well, did you work for Bill Harris?
I guess I could.
He said, well, that's the guy.
So he got on his bicycle, rode up, and told me.
And that's the first time I knew about it.
And that afternoon, I got a call from the plant manager.
He called me then, asked me if I thought I could handle it.
And I said, well, if I get into trouble, I guess I ought to do the same.
OK, he said.
So, that was a big job, by the way.
That was one of the best jobs in town.
I bet he went and broke all his buttons off his chest.
What year was that now?
That would be 1938.
Maybe 38, I think.
Anyhow,
After the first day or two, which were absolute hell, everything went fine, and I had a real good job.
Actually, when I graduated and decided I'd have to go back east to get a job as a chem engineer, I told the plant manager, and I actually cried because I was leaving.
So he kind of liked me.
And it turns out, I think, that I decided I'd been better off nationally by staying there and going back east.
But as a chem engineer, I had to do my thing.
Went back to Buffalo, New York,
I got a job with National Handling Division of Analytic Chemical and Dye, which is a company that makes dye stuff.
At that time, most of all the chemistry industry involved coal-tar chemistry.
I started out with benzene, naphthalene, built up an entire industry from that.
It was a very fun job because everything was batch chemistry.
and they ran almost every reaction that's known except the Denard reaction.
So I had a lot of opportunity to learn a lot about industrial chemistry, although I was a chem engineer, they considered me a chemist.
I started there as a production worker, and I guess I made so many waves telling them how to do it this way or that way, they put me over in research and development.
I and one other chem engineering BS were the only
people in the research department that didn't have PhDs in chemistry, which made us kind of weird.

And I wasn't too hot in chemistry anyhow, so I ended up taking the processes that most of the chemists would develop and working on them and making them a practical process for the industry to put out into the plant.
Because they'd do things like 13 ether extractions or something like that.
We just totally paused for that.
But that's what I came up with.
Right.
And so I worked for the
the intermediates group as their, I guess you'd say, liaison between application and research.
It was a great job.
The war broke out.
I got an industrial deferment.
I tried to enter the Navy because we had to get an engine sprang in.
got that shot down real fast.
They needed training in industrial chemistry.
Did Allied Chemical move into war production?
They did some, but of course things like Cagney Dye and so forth.
Yeah, that's right.
But really what kind of got going thereafter, I did a number of things.
I worked on some war gases, things like that.

One thing's not generally known, we didn't do much fighting over in the east for about two years after the war broke out, because, well, the Japanese had taken over Indonesia and these other countries that produced quinine, and all of them were heavily infested with malaria, and it was just impractical to invade these islands and not have any kind of quinine available.
And finally the Americans from North Africa captured some German soldiers,
and found they were taking a pill that the vermin had developed as an asymptote for one brain, for adrenoplinicrin.
They sent the pills over to us and said we need tons of this stuff as soon as possible.
So three of us took on the job of synthesizing that and working with the production team.
Did Allied chemical manufacturers start making it?
Oh yes, they started making it.
That was kind of an interesting thing.
It turned out everybody took it yellow.
Most of the soldiers can remember taking it.
I almost remember that stuff.
I didn't take it, but I remember people talking about it.
I remember one of the funny things is I walked in and we had a polar lab.
One of my friends was down there.
I went down to see him and went into the lab where he had a black light on.
It scared the hell out of me.
I glowed.
I glowed all over like one of those Halloween skeletons or something.
That kind of scared me for a bit.
But anyhow, the Battle of the Bows came along.
And that was a lot more serious than most people thought because immediately they canceled all industrial referments for 126, including mine.
I got a notice immediately from the Colorado draft board saying report down for termination.
And so I reported for an exam, went through what I thought were flying colors.
came up to the final guy who did the stamping and he looked at me and looked at the thing and he looked back at me and he reached over and he got a big stamp saying reject me.
And I started to argue with him.
I didn't know what the hell.
Got home and my wife was really excited.
She had gotten a telegram from the backboard saying to ignore the exam.
She had gotten a telegram from Brigadier General Drum of New York Selecting Service saying that he had assumed
jurisdiction of my thing, and that I was to ignore the Italian.
Got another one from the portion of D.C. somewhere.
Forget everything.
Then we got some kind of a message from the plant saying to ignore the old thing, but it all came after I had my cancer.
So there was a pretty concerted effort to keep me in the malaria business, I guess.
There were two of us out of 26 that were under that age that didn't get picked up.
I kind of resented it in a way, but I could understand the whole thing.
My wife thought it was great.
She didn't want me to do it at all.
Do I have kids at that time?
I have one.
At that time I had one.
Maybe I had to, I'm not sure.
But anyhow, I didn't like New York very well.
Again, in the West, that's kind of the problem, I think.
I particularly didn't like Buffalo, which had a beautiful country that had a perfectly precious climate.
I couldn't move because of the war, of course.
Mike pointed out also that I couldn't get very many raises.
The only people who got raises during the war were people who won the unions.
It was kind of funny because almost every employee in the plant that was working made more money than the superintendents did.
Because they could get raises, and we couldn't.
So, some of the guys working for me, particularly with their overtime, would make two or three times as much as I made.
I knew that.
You know, they had the wage price freeze everywhere, but they never told them that the unions were out of that.
It kind of got me into trouble.
My brother-in-law, who had an eighth grade education, worked for Curtis Wright Airplanes, twice in cables.
And he made almost four times as much as I made.
We got into college and so forth.
And boy, do you think my in-laws didn't learn it.
Let you know about it.
But actually, it took me probably 20 years before I could catch up with him, you know, afterwards.
Yeah.
It was quite a... That's something, yeah, and that is another story.
What a deal.
But anyhow, as soon as the war was over, I got a job out in the Apache powder company.
Supposed to be in the Apache region, Arizona, Pennsylvania or something.
Where is Benson?
It's about 50 miles east of Tucson.
Okay.
And at that time there were 960 people in the population, and about half of them were Hispanic.
Very few yards from town, in a typical desert.
Yeah.
Is that on the highway out there?
It's on the highway now.
We go through this, I mean through Arizona a lot, through Tucson and Phoenix.
It's on that highway.
What kind of powder?
It's about 20 miles north of Tombstone.
Military contracts?
Powder?
No, this company actually is the largest commercial explosives company in the world.
It was owned by Phelps Dodge, Kennecott, Anaconda, all these big companies that mine out in the west.
Oh, okay.

And that was, I went out there as an engineer, but I became a technical supervisor in a couple years, so I was in charge of, you know, let's see, product control, customer service, research and development, engineering and development, safety.
That kind of thing.
Everything except the actual manufacturing.
Did you have any loading or something?
We had three loads there.
All of them, I think, do.
One guy, we don't understand why.
We feel it.
Initially, we all feel it.
Yeah, we didn't know, but it was apparently, it was a practice.
We had a lot of problems in one thing or another.
And the last one caught him about halfway away from the building, about two blocks, and picked him up and was tearing his skin to like a rag.
And he had a lot of matches and stuff like that.
I mean, this was actually the day of it.
So, I think he probably would settle on three of them, if you don't know that.
I know one of them was your friend, the psychiatrist.
It's like you had the evaluation for 104, didn't you?
Yeah, I guess so.
I know that's what happened.
The, uh, I liked that job.
That was a good job.
He paid well.
I had a chance to do things like go down to New Mexico and end up in mines up in the world, in old buildings and get asked around how to use explosives and this kind of thing.
I met very interesting people because all the people in these mines are weird.
They have a Ph.D. from Marquette University.
They're up there with us.
That's why they're there.
They haven't been to a dentist for 20 years.
They have the packages coming down their beard and that kind of stuff.
They're weird people.
but it's interesting, nevertheless.
I think the history of the Forest Service in the South, that's what I do on the side, in the Southwest region, in Arizona and Mexico, and in the Montana area, there's a lot of these minor types.
Well, they're weird.
And in Alaska.
I mean, a lot of them.
What I never could figure out is you see an ad for one of these mining engineers, and it goes something like this.
Do you want a mining engineer who has a Ph.D.,
can speak Spanish, Chinese, and English fluently, has 20 years experience, $200 a month for some stupid figure like that, and they apparently found them.
That's what I could never figure out.
You'd think a guy like that would be worth a lot more money, but that's a different world.
Anyhow, my wife did not like Arizona.
There was, like I say, no grass in any of the yards.
Pretty much a man's country.
If you like to hunt or prospect and this kind of thing, I agree that we wanted to be there.
Back there, the barbecuers up there wasn't very nice.
She didn't like the explosive business.
I don't think we need to go into why I decided to quit.
But anyhow, I decided to quit.
I told her and she said, fine, let's go back to where my mother lives.
I said, no way.
We'll move halfway and we're going to find a place that's got a
reasonable climate, good schools, and a job with some dignity, and they don't give a damn if I ever become a plant manager anymore.
I've given up on it.
I had to find out that the more you became a plant manager, the more hours you put in.
But anyhow, I found this job at A&M.
How?
How?
How did that happen?
How did I find the one?
They had advertised on the Kennedy Engineering News for an engineer, and I answered it.
I thought maybe there was a connection somewhere.
Well, I just followed up on an ad.
I came here as an associate research engineer.
Who was head of that lab?
Cecil Womble was head of it.
It was kind of an interesting job.
It wasn't too challenging.
At that time, the cottonseed industry was probably at its peak.
They had about somewhere around 450-500 cottonseed mills in the state.
They had a strong organization called the Cotton Mill Superintendent's Association.
None of these outfits, except for Anderson, Clayton, and a couple others were big enough to do any research or so forth.
So they managed to get this program going, which was a really good program.
It was basically funded by the... Well, it was funded by the state, but the association had enough political plot to get the state to fund it.
The Cotton Seed Research Council, established by the state, was split into three.
The Texas Bulls branch of it, I think, to Texas Tech.
The homemakers, the laundering, the shirts, and that kind of stuff, to Colorado Women's College, or not Colorado, Texas Women's College somewhere.
And then the technical production came in.
Do you remember if the Textile Engineering Program was still here, or anything like that?
Do you remember anything like that?
I don't recall that.
We had a thing called the...
I think it had gone on.
Institute of Oil... Institute of Oil... Continental Oil Technology or something like that.
It was sort of a paper...
We had a textile engineering program for a while in the 20s and 30s.
I think it was Dan Wall.
That part of it was handled by Les.
He handled the mill.
actually what really sort of happened there was was his name perhaps george s perhaps he was the state chemist back in the 40s and 30s you know we our revelation in the
state chemists was primary because they analyzed the protein content and so forth.
They had to understand the standards and of course part of our problem was to make sure they managed to do this right.
It's kind of an interesting thing because the protein is the expensive part.
You lose money if you sell 43% of the time.
You're breaking the law if you sell anything under 41% of the time.
So you've got an urge to cut down with a club hanging over your neck if you cut too far.
So to try and keep just above that level is a pretty trickier thing, which brings up this kind of thought.
These all-now superintendents, by and large, were very intelligent men who had a limited education.
They usually started out in the automobile operation and they were smart enough and so forth to become superintendents.
But being intelligent and having worked their way up like that, they were pretty self-confident folks.
Which meant that it was pretty hard to tell them as an engineer.
So, for example, on this protein thing, the way they would do it is send out a sample every day to their commercial lab to be analyzed.
They came back a little high, they made an adjustment a little early, they were making an adjustment.
And I remember working out the statistical quality control on it and showing that the results of the analysis had plus or minus a half percent.
So if you come back with two percent, two tenths of a percent higher or something like that, that doesn't mean you want to make any adjustments at all.
And worked it out to where they could send out a sample about once a week and actually do a better job for the rest.
There you go.
Well, I'll give you an example of that.
They have these big, huge fans that pull air through cottonsea plows and they've got 100 horsepower motors on them.
I mean, they're big.
If they had a pool of cottonsea, you could just blow it.
I'm from Niagara, so yeah, we have a big... Oh, you remember here in the... Yeah, yeah.
Now, basically these fans were discharging through about a 10 by 16 inch discharge through, bam, out into the atmosphere.
Which made a hell of a lot of noise and so forth.
But more than that, it created, there's a thing called a power recover.
If you expand that gas through it like a megaphone, in about a seven degree angle megaphone, the kinetic energy in the gas
which is pretty high because it's coming out there at, you know, the value of a sailor or something of a high volume, is recovered.
And it turns out you can recover about 10% of your energy just by putting a diverging nozzle under this.
This is well-known.
In fact, it's...
March's mechanical engineering handbook has a whole page on how to design a power recovery for fans.
So I wrote an article suggesting that all these guys should put these on.
It would cost them maybe $100 to have one made in a sheet metal shop that would A. cut down all that noise, B. they would recover 10% of their power.
I even went with suppliers to some of these superintendents.
They're watching the page out of the handbook and sending it to me.
And using such things the same way.
Look, if I put an electric fan in front of this discharge, it would turn that fan, right?
Well, that fan could be generating electricity, right?
Well, that's energy that you're losing.
Guess how many people are using power recovery units on their fans?
Not a whole lot of people.
Not a lot of people.
No, they've been doing this for years.
They've been working on it.
They still won't do it.
No, they still won't do it.
But as they're getting back to the research business, in a way, the time seems to have sorted for itself.
And the oil mill's out of business, because what happened is they went from screw extraction to solid extraction, which is amenable to larger-scale production, more efficiency.
And our lab did a great deal of the work on that, showing how to do it.
And that result is, I don't know how many oil mill operations there are in the state now, but I would bet it's probably less than 20.
They've gone to year-round extraction using solvent extraction, which a small plant like you used to have an oil mill down here and have a soda.
with us too, you know, we couldn't possibly compete.
So all these guys, the whole industry has changed dramatically because of the results of this.
I did some work over in the history of the rice industry.
I got really into rice when I was in New Zealand.
And they were just starting to work with the chemical dimming processes.
I don't think that ever has really become commercial.
I don't know whether it's ever really been adopted.
I don't really know much about it, except for the rice oil.
But it sounds like it applies pretty much to what?
Did you do what?
Did you?
Yeah.
Did you do it?
Exactly.
In fact, I went to Beaumont about a few weeks ago and bought back six bags of rice hulls and put them in my garden to make some really good compost.
And now I'm going to plow it up this spring and get this hull and mulch it clean and start it out the original way.
We pick them on how much absorbance they have.
For example, we use crushed peach pits.
because they're not important.
Sometimes you don't want the carbonaceous to absorb in that condition because it reduces its sensitivity.
So you have a whole progression in 20 or 30 ingredients that you use for different purposes.
Well, many of the potency labs
It was kind of fun.
It gave me a chance to go out and visit a lot of wild animals and small town rural Texas, which to me, I guess I'm just a rural farmer at heart.
When Dr. Calhoun came here, he was an engineer.
He looked around at what A&M was doing, and he saw a lot of guys like myself who were full-time research engineers, and a bunch of cops who weren't doing any research.
He said, that's not the way it's supposed to work.
Every cop should be doing research, and every researcher ought to be teaching.
So, this was actually on a Friday.
One Friday, I got a phone call from Dr. Lindsay, who was in the engineering department, telling me that I was going to start teaching, following Monday.
I explained to him that I hadn't been in a classroom for a long time.
He said, that's alright, you don't know what the students do.
And Monday I was, quote, teaching.
What were you teaching?
I started out teaching
The real interesting thing there, I was making pretty good money as an associate research engineer, but since I only had a bachelor of science degree, they didn't want to call me a professor.
Fred Benson, who was then head of the experiment station, said, no, wait a minute.
If we hire a prof to give them jobs during the summer to work as research engineers, we're going to tease.
We pay them according to their power as profs.
My God, if you hire a research engineer that's a prof, you're going to pay him and give him the title of a prof.
I wonder, didn't
Did Benson and Calhoun get along real good?
I can't remember.
I don't know.
I have no idea.
They must have gotten along pretty well.
They worked.
Let me tell you, just a sideline.
Benson, to me, is one of the greatest men I have ever met.
A lot of people think that?
Absolutely.
He had a knack for picking not-so-good subordinates.
He was...
Well, this is a story I just told you.
It's an example.
He didn't think that was right, and by God, we're going to do what's right.
I don't know how many profs there were on the campus, associate profs, that had just a BS degree, but I suspect I was maybe one of them.
Alone, or maybe two or three of us would be the most I would think.
Well, there was no great professional engineers to get the day off the gate.
Well, a long time.
Anyhow, that did hold me back.
I started on a master's degree when I came here, because when I came here, my idea was to work through college and go to school.
And I started on the master's degree, and while I'm working on the master's degree, they made this rule which

make some sense that they wouldn't grant any advanced degrees to anyone who had a uh well by the time i was uh got out of my master's i had a uh i was a professor and they wouldn't let me go for a phd yeah i could take a lot of courses and i took i thought i'd taken more courses than graduate school anybody in this campus didn't look at that all the graduate courses
They did both of them in chemistry and statistics, and blue transfer, all kinds of good stuff.
Anyhow, I couldn't get an advanced degree, and that held me back quite a bit.
There was a lot of expansion in salaries during the 50s, and I kind of got pretty well chatteled in on that, because I did not have a degree.
And along about 69, the legislature passed this thing saying that the college would grant sabbatical leave.
Good thing.
And it worked out so you could have six months full pay or a year for half pay.
And I thought, well, that sounds pretty good.
I called up the Colorado State University.
That's right next to it.
We loved them when I was a kid.
And I loved the mountains.
That's a good place to do school.
But then I talked to the guy up there.
And he says, yeah.
and the fact is that even let me use my research that I've done, and the fact of the research, because it was right down the alley what they were doing.
It wasn't in ag engineering, but what I was doing was working with the wall there through toxic files, which is, in technical terms, fluid flow through porous, non-homogeneous, anisotropic
And they were working with water and aquifers for producing the irrigation water and that kind of thing.
Same identical equations, everything the same.
And so it was not something that was foreign to what they were doing, except it was in the ag engineering department at Colorado State.
So I took a sabbatical leave and applied for one and immediately got shot down.
The rules had to do with appoint or somehow get a committee of professors who would administer the sabbatical leave program.
The very first rule they passed when they met, we will not grant sabbatical leaves for anyone working for an advanced degree.
They wanted you to be, take one and go out and write a book or do something like that.
Well, that screwed me right off the bat.
And I talked to, I guess, Dean Benson.
I talked to Dean Benson, and he says, well, my guy, he says, if I remember that law, it says that each branch of the college can have its own sabbatical league committee.
And by God, I'm going to appoint a committee for the T's, because you work half time for T's.
And by God, they're going to grant you a sabbatical leave.
Very good.
Well, I didn't think I'd be like this.
Well, it was the right thing to do.
You know?
And it's very typical of Dean Benson.
I tell you, he's one of the greatest men I've ever met.
They're certainly more than responsible for these meetings.
But anyhow, I did take a sabbatical leave.
I went up to Colorado where I...
This is probably a world record.
I got a Ph.D. in one year.
That sounds like a record to me.
I don't believe anybody's ever been bad.
No, I don't think so either.
But it is a Ph.D. in agricultural engineering.
I got up there and the first semester went through and I was selling my stock.
When I got it, it dropped from 60 down to about 20.
I figured, man, I don't want to sell that stuff.
And I walked into the Department of Law office one day with my mail, grouching out loud, you know, that I don't know what I'm going to do.
I just don't want to sell that stock.
I'm short on money and all the wrong mail.
It shows the importance of being nice to people.
And I've always been nice to the secretary there.
She's always been nice to the secretary.
She's the chief of the day.
And she heard me.
She went back in.
She says, well, you know something.
The School of Engineering, or Graduate School of Engineering has a scholarship for the outstanding scholar in the graduate school.
She said, I seem to remember you've made all A's.
I said, yeah.
Well, I'm going to apply for that for you.
I said, okay, go ahead.
I didn't think anything about it.
About three weeks later, I'm going to be on my last scholarship.
I didn't have to be wonderful.
I didn't have to sell my stock.
I hope your stock went back up.
No, it didn't.
I finally sold it.
But anyhow, I think it was...
a good, pure indication of why a page had good manners.
Really.
She didn't need to do that.
It was actually effort on her part.
